@NODE 0. "Overview"
 
 Thank you  for acquiring AmiCFA. The program has been written to assist you
 in  creating  the  header  and  other  files  necessary  for  the 'COMPUTER
 FLOHMARKT' computer zeitschrift for kleinanzeigen.
 
 Note:  Although  the  program  has been  given  the  kind  blessing  of the
 'COMPUTER FLOHMARKT' team, the program author and the program itself are in
 no  way connected to   the 'COMPUTER FLOHMARKT'.   Criticisms, Bug reports,
 comments, etc. must be directed  to:
 
 Douglas M Hess
 Krämerstr. 26
 D-63450 Hanau
 eMail: dmhess@t-online.de
 
@{" AmiCFA " Link 0.0.}
@{" Msh " Link 0.1.}
@{" The Manual " Link 0.2.}
@{" Legal " Link 0.3.}
@{" Registering AmiCFA " Link 0.4.}
@ENDNODE

@NODE 0.0. "AmiCFA"
 
 The  program has been  made as  user-friendly as  possible. AmiCFA actually
 contains several editors and utilities 'rolled' into one program!
 
 *    The  'User' functions allow you to easily  manage text for yourself as
      well as others. The number of users that can be managed is only limited
      by your disk space!
 *    Creating or editing your header file is easy with the header editor.
 *    A  custom database  program is  also available  to manage  'biete' and
      'suche' software lists.
 *    The built-in  text editor allows you to type your text without leaving
      the program!
 *    After  the data is complete, you only  click on the 'Create' button to
      write the finished files to the disk of your choice.
 
 AmiCFA requires 1 megabyte of RAM and a harddisk or second disk drive.
 
@ENDNODE

@NODE 0.1. "Msh"
 
 Short:         read/write filesystem for pc floppies.
 Long: Msh:     An  Amiga   file  system  handler  that  handles  MSDOS
                formatted  diskettes. Version  "1.30" (Release  1 patch
                3).   You can use files on such disks in almost exactly
                the same way as you use files on native AmigaDOS disks.
                This  is a  fully functional,  read/write version, that
                supports  8, 9,  or 10 sector  disks of  80 tracks, and
                should also work on 40 track drives and hard disks with
                12  or  16 bit  FAT of  any  dimension the  FAT allows.
                Update  to  version  "1.5"  (Release  1)  on  disk 327.
                Includes source. Author: Olaf Seibert
 
 With the  kind permission of Olaf Seibert, the Msh device has been included
 with AmiCFA. Please note, Msh is a freely distributable program package and
 that  donations  to its  author  are  welcome.The entire  Msh  package with
 utilities  and  source  code  is  located  in the  drawer 'Msh_1_30'.

 The  newest  version  of "Msh" is  1.56 and  it even  handles  high-density
 floppies. Version 1.56 is available on the Aminet.
 
@ENDNODE

@NODE 0.2. "The Manual"
 
 How is this manual arranged?
 The manual is divided into three sections:
 'Install', 'Quick-Start', and 'Reference'.
 Install gets  you set up and running. The Quick-Start section will have you
 writing ads in a few minutes. The Reference section describes the functions
 and  features of AmiCFA in detail and  also answers the most commonly asked
 questions.

@{" Installing AmiCFA " Link 0.2.0.}
@{" Installing 'Msh' " Link 0.2.1.}
@{" Quick Start: AmiCFA " Link 0.2.2.}
@{" Quick Start: Msh " Link 0.2.3.}
@{" Reference: AmiCFA " Link 0.2.4.}
@ENDNODE

@NODE 0.2.0. "Installing AmiCFA"
 
@{" For systems with two floppy drives and no harddisk " Link 0.2.0.0.}
@{" For systems with a harddisk " Link 0.2.0.1.}
@ENDNODE

@NODE 0.2.0.0. "For systems with two floppy drives and no harddisk"
 
 To  avoid  unnecessary disk  swaps,  'AmiCFA'should  be installed  on  to a
 bootable Workbench diskette.
 
 
 1.)    copy   a   complete  Workbench   diskette   and  relabel   the  copy
        "AmiCFA_Work".
 
 2.)    start your computer new with "AmiCFA_Work".
 
 3.)    insert  the "AmiCFA" diskette  and double-click on  its disk icon to
        view its  contents.  The following icons will be seen in the "AmiCFA"
        window:
 
 MakeRoom13.Script   makes room  for AmiCFA  on a  Workbench 1.3 boot
                     diskette labeled "AmiCFA_Work".
 MakeRoom20.Script   makes room  for AmiCFA  on a  Workbench 2.0 boot
                     diskette labeled "AmiCFA_Work".
 MakeRoom30.Script   makes room  for AmiCFA  on a  Workbench 3.0 boot
                     diskette labeled "AmiCFA_Work".
 Install_Msh.Script  installs the  Msh files to  your boot partition or
                     diskette.
 AmiCFA              drawer containing the AmiCFA program and data.
 
 4.)    to make  enough room (about 311K) on the 'AmiCFA_Work' disk, double-
        click on the 'MakeRoomXX.Script'. (Use the script with your Workbench
        version in place of the XX.) Wait for all disk activity to cease.
 
 5.)    drag  the 'AmiCFA' drawer icon from  the 'AmiCFA' window and release
        it  over the  'AmiCFA_Work' icon  and wait  for all  disk activity to
        cease.  Close the 'AmiCFA' window.
 
 6.)    'AmiCFA'  is now installed. If you wish  to use 'Msh' to read, write
        to,   and  format  MS-DOS  compatible   diskettes,  please  read  the
        instructions on how to install 'Msh'.
 
@ENDNODE

@NODE 0.2.0.1. "For systems with a harddisk"
 
 1.)    insert  the "AmiCFA" diskette  and double-click on  its disk icon to
        view its  contents.  The following icons will be seen in the "AmiCFA"
        window:
 
 MakeRoom13.Script   makes room  for AmiCFA  on a  Workbench 1.3 boot
                     diskette labeled "AmiCFA_Work".
 MakeRoom20.Script   makes room  for AmiCFA  on a  Workbench 2.0 boot
                     diskette labeled "AmiCFA_Work".
 MakeRoom30.Script   makes room  for AmiCFA  on a  Workbench 3.0 boot
                     diskette labeled "AmiCFA_Work".
 Install_Msh.Script  installs the  Msh files to  your boot partition on or
                     diskette.
 AmiCFA              drawer containing the AmiCFA program and data.
 
 2.)    drag  the 'AmiCFA' drawer icon from  the 'AmiCFA' window and release
        it over  the desired harddisk destination. Wait for all disk activity
        to cease.  Close the 'AmiCFA' window.
 
 3.)    'AmiCFA'  is now installed. If you wish  to use 'Msh' to read, write
        to,   and  format  MS-DOS  compatible   diskettes,  please  read  the
        instructions on how to install 'Msh'.
 
@ENDNODE

@NODE 0.2.1. "Installing 'Msh'"
 
 1.)    Boot  your system with the diskette or  partition that you will boot
        with when using 'AmiCFA'.
 
 2.)    insert  the "AmiCFA" diskette  and double-click on  its disk icon to
        view  its contents. The following icons will  be seen in the "AmiCFA"
        window:
 
 MakeRoom13.Script   makes room  for AmiCFA  on a  Workbench 1.3 boot
                     diskette labeled "AmiCFA_Work".
 MakeRoom20.Script   makes room  for AmiCFA  on a  Workbench 2.0 boot
                     diskette labeled "AmiCFA_Work".
 MakeRoom30.Script   makes room  for AmiCFA  on a  Workbench 3.0 boot
                     diskette labeled "AmiCFA_Work".
 Install_Msh.Script  installs the  Msh files to  your boot partition or
                     diskette.
 AmiCFA              drawer containing the AmiCFA program and data.
 
 3.)    double-click  on  the  'Install_Msh.Script'.  After  all disk
        activity  has ceased,  Msh  has  been installed  on  your boot
        diskette or partition.
 
@ENDNODE

@NODE 0.2.2. "Quick Start: AmiCFA"

@{" Starting the program " Link 0.2.2.0.}
@{" Step 1: Selecting a User " Link 0.2.2.1.}
@{" Step 2: Creating a header " Link 0.2.2.2.}
@{" Step 3: Entering the text " Link 0.2.2.3.}
@{" Step 4: Selecting a rubrik " Link 0.2.2.4.}
@{" Step 5: Selecting end-variables " Link 0.2.2.5.}
@{" Step 6: saving your text " Link 0.2.2.6.}
@{" Step 7: Creating additional ads " Link 0.2.2.7.}
@{" Step 8: Preparing your text for 'CF' " Link 0.2.2.8.}
@{" Step 9: Sending in your data " Link 0.2.2.9.}
@ENDNODE

@NODE 0.2.2.0. "Starting the program"

 After starting  AmiCFA with a double click on the program icon, you will be
 presented with the  main control panel.  On the side of the panel is a list
 gadget  containing names of  all 'Users'.   At the moment  only one name is
 being  displayed...'User1'.   We  will begin  by going  through all  of the
 necessary  steps to create the  different CFA files  for an imaginary user,
 'User1'.

@ENDNODE

@NODE 0.2.2.1. "Step 1: Selecting a User"

 Select  the user whose  data you will  be editing or  creating. To select a
 user, just  click on his or her name in  the list.  After selecting a user,
 all  actions  taken will  effect  that user's  data  until another  user is
 selected or the program is ended.
 
@ENDNODE

@NODE 0.2.2.2. "Step 2: Creating a header"

 Creating  a 'Header'  should always  be done  immediately after  creating a
 'User'. Once  a Header has been created for a  User it will only have to be
 edited  when information  changes for  that User.   To  create or  edit the
 Header, click on the 'Edit Header'on the main control panel. Enter the data
 for  'User1' in the text  gadgets. Click on the  'Save' button to write the
 information to disk and return to the main control panel.
 
@ENDNODE

@NODE 0.2.2.3. "Step 3: Entering the text"

 Click  on 'CF' button  in the 'Edit  section' of the  main control panel to
 enter  the text editor. Type  the desired text into  the large text editing
 area.
 
@ENDNODE

@NODE 0.2.2.4. "Step 4: Selecting a rubrik"

 Enter  the rubrik selector by  clicking on the 'Rubrik'  button. Click on a
 topic displayed  in the huge list gadget. A list of sub-topics will then be
 shown.  Click on a sub-topic  in the list window.  (If BIETE, SUCHE, FRAGE,
 ANTWORT, or INFO  appear at the end of the sub-topic, click on one of these
 words.). If you wish to change the main topic, click on the small button to
 right of the upper text gadget. Click on 'Return' when finished
 
@ENDNODE

@NODE 0.2.2.5. "Step 5: Selecting end-variables"

 The end  variables that you select determine what information will be shown
 at  the  bottom  of  your current  text  when  published  in  the 'Computer
 Flohmarkt'.  If  readers are  to contact  you  by mail,  then click  on the
 'ANSCHRIFT'  button. This will cause all of  your address information to be
 printed.  If 'CF' readers  are to contact  you by phone,  then click on the
 'VORNAME'  and 'TELEFON' buttons. If you wish  to change your choice, click
 on the 'Start again' button. Click on 'Return' when you are finished.
 
@ENDNODE

@NODE 0.2.2.6. "Step 6: saving your text"

 Click  on the 'Save'  button. If you have  not yet given  your text a name,
 a requester will appear to ask you for a name. Delete the text in the lower
 text  gadget and enter  the name of your  text. Click on  'Ok' to save your
 text.
 
@ENDNODE

@NODE 0.2.2.7. "Step 7: Creating additional ads"

 If  you wish to create another  ad, click on the  'New' button to clear the
 old text.  Repeat steps 3 to 6 for each  new ad. When saving your text, try
 to  use descriptive names to  assist you in finding  a particular ad if you
 should wish to change it later.
 
@ENDNODE

@NODE 0.2.2.8. "Step 8: Preparing your text for 'CF'"

 Workbench  2.1+ users should mount  'PC0:' before continuing. Workbench 1.3
 and  2.0 users should mount  'MS0:'. (Please refer  to the 'Msh QuickStart'
 section for more information about 'Msh'.)

 NOTE: A text converter, ie. CrossDOS, is not necessary.

 Click  on the 'Return'  button to return  to the main  program window. Then
 click  on the 'CF'  button in the  'Create .txt' section.  A file requester
 will  appear with 'RAM:' as  the default directory.  Click on the 'Volumes'
 button to  display all of the mounted volumes. If the name of your diskette
 is not visible in the list, scroll the list using the scroll bar located on
 the right side.  Click on the name of your diskette in the list and then on
 'Ok'. You  will then be asked if you wish  to delete the text files. If you
 answer  'Yes, AmiCFA will delete  the text files as  it writes the 'CF.TXT'
 file.  If you answer  'No', the text files  will not be  deleted. This is a
 good option if should you want to use the text again. Click on one of these
 two buttons and AmiCFA will write your file to disk.
 
@ENDNODE

@NODE 0.2.2.9. "Step 9: Sending in your data"

 Please  read  the instructions  in   the  latest edition  of  the 'Computer
 Flohmarkt' for details. Here is a partial list of things to be aware of:

 *    Label your diskette with your name, address, and telephone number.

 *    If  you have filled in  the 'Pseudo' field,  fill out a 'Pseudoantrag'
      and  include it  with  the diskette.  This is  only necessary  if your
      pseudo is not already in the pseudo list.

 *    If sending in a 'Biete' or 'Suche' software list, fill out the address
      portion  of  the 'Biete'  or  'Suche'  form located  in  the 'Computer
      Flohmarkt' and send it in with your diskette.

 *    Please  check the diskette for virus' before  sending it to 'CF'. Also
      ensure that only the files needed by the 'CF' are on the disk.

 *    Disks will not be returned.

 *    Here is the address:
      --------------------

      Computer-Flohmarkt
      Postfach 66
      D-75430 Maulbronn
      Germany

 *    You can also upload your text to the CF mailbox:
      ------------------------------------------------

      Phone number        = ++49-7043-33446
      password (kennwort) = CF
      username            = CF

@ENDNODE

@NODE 0.2.3. "Quick Start: Msh"
 
 For the  purpose of this example we will assume that your external drive is
 "df1:".  Place   the  disk  to  be  formatted  to  720K  in  df1:  and  the
 "AmiCFA_Work" disk in "df0".
 Open a "CLI" or "Shell" window. In this window, type:
 
 1>mount ms1:<Return>
 1>messyfmt 1<Return>
 
 answer the prompts with <Return> until the following appears:
 
 Format whole disk (enter 1)? [0]
 
 type: 1<Return>
 then the following will appear:
 
 Are you sure? (enter 42)? [0]
 
 If you just hit <Return> then the disk will not be formatted. To format the
 disk type: 42<Return>
 
 The  computer will begin formatting  the disk in drive  1. Progress will be
 shown on the screen. When finished the following will appear:
 
 Now remove the disk from the drive (or use DiskChange).
 1>
 
 type: diskchange ms1:<Return>
 
 You  should  now have  an icon  with  the name  "DF1:BAD" or  "DF1:???" and
 another with  the name "Unnamed". The "Unnamed" disk icon is the 720K disk.
 Files  may be written to or  from the 720K disk as  with any other disk. If
 you now remove the disk and replace it with another, the diskchange will be
 recognised automatically.  You may now close the CLI window and continue on
 with your work.
 
@ENDNODE

@NODE 0.2.4. "Reference: AmiCFA"
 
@{" user window " Link 0.2.4.0.}
@{" header editor " Link 0.2.4.1.}
@{" text editor " Link 0.2.4.2.}
@{" rubrik selector " Link 0.2.4.3.}
@{" end variable selector " Link 0.2.4.4.}
@{" database editor " Link 0.2.4.5.}
@ENDNODE

@NODE 0.2.4.0. "user window"
 
 After starting  AmiCFA with a double-click on the program icon, you will be
 presented with the 'user window'. The 'user window' is divided into several
 sections:
 1.   a 'user list',
 2.   a 'user section' containing 'add', 'delete', and 'rename'buttons,
 3.   a 'header section' containing an 'edit header' button,
 4.   an 'edit section' containing 'cf' 'biete' and 'suche' buttons,
 5.   a  'create .txt section' also  containing 'cf' 'biete' and 'suche'
     buttons.
 
@{" user list " Link 0.2.4.0.0.}
@{" user section " Link 0.2.4.0.1.}
@{" header section " Link 0.2.4.0.2.}
@{" edit section " Link 0.2.4.0.3.}
@{" create .txt section " Link 0.2.4.0.4.}
@ENDNODE

@NODE 0.2.4.0.0. "user list"
 
 The  'user list'  is located  in the  upper left-hand  corner of  the 'user
 window'.  The  current user  is  always  highlighted. Another  user  can be
 selected by clicking  on the name in the 'user list'. If no users have been
 created  the 'user list' will  be blank.  All  buttons in the 'user window'
 affect the user that is highlighted in the 'user list'.
 
@ENDNODE

@NODE 0.2.4.0.1. "user section"
 
 The  'user  section'  contains  three  buttons  that  affect  the currently
 selected user.
 
 The 'add'  button in the 'user section' is used  to add a name to the 'user
 list'.  At least one user must  be entered into the  'user list' for you to
 use  the  program. Most  of the  time  only one  user is  needed, yourself.
 However, those  who also wish to manage data for friends, businesses, etc.,
 will find the 'user section' functions very handy.
 
 The 'delete' and 'rename' buttons in the 'user section' allow the currently
 selected user  to be renamed or deleted.   Be aware that deleting a user is
 permanent  and  that  all of  the  deleted  data, header,  texts,  etc., is
 irretrievably lost.
 
@ENDNODE

@NODE 0.2.4.0.2. "header section"
 
 The  'Edit Header'  button in  the 'header  section' activates  the 'header
 editor'. This is where the header information is entered or changed.
 
@ENDNODE

@NODE 0.2.4.0.3. "edit section"
 
 The 'CF'  button in the 'edit section' activates the 'text editor'. This is
 where ads are written.
 The  'Biete' button in the 'edit  section' activates the built-in 'database
 editor'  for creating and editing  lists of software that  is to be offered
 for sale.
 
 The  'Suche' button in the 'edit'  section activates the built-in 'database
 editor'  for  creating  and editing  lists  of  software that  you  wish to
 purchase.
 
@ENDNODE

@NODE 0.2.4.0.4. "create .txt section"
 
 The 'CF'  button in the 'create .txt section'  writes all ads present for a
 user  and his  header information  to disk.  The name  of the  file written
 should be  cf.txt for the first cf file  written and cf2.txt for the second
 file  written to the same  disk. Subsequent files  should be named cf3.txt,
 cf4.txt, etc. Only one cf file should be present on the disk for each user.
 Please  see the  current edition of  'Computer Flohmarkt'  for details. You
 will be asked if the text files should be deleted, if you select 'yes' then
 the text  files will be deleted as the cf  file is written to disk. You may
 also select  'no' and delete the files manually from the 'text editor' (the
 safest method).
 
 The  'biete' button in the 'create .txt  section' writes the biete software
 list  for a user and his  header information to disk.  The name of the file
 written  should  be  cfbiete1.txt  for the  first  biete  file  written and
 cfbiete2.txt for the second file written to the same disk. Subsequent files
 should be named cfbiete3.txt, cfbiete4.txt, etc. Only one biete file should
 be  present on the  disk for each  user. Please see  the current edition of
 'Computer Flohmarkt' for details.
 
 The  'suche' button in the 'create .txt  section' writes the suche software
 list  for a user and his  header information to disk.  The name of the file
 written  should  be  cfsuche1.txt  for the  first  suche  file  written and
 cfsuche2.txt for the second file written to the same disk. Subsequent files
 should be named cfsuche3.txt, cfsuche4.txt, etc. Only one suche file should
 be  present on the  disk for each  user. Please see  the current edition of
 'Computer Flohmarkt' for details.
 
@ENDNODE

@NODE 0.2.4.1. "header editor"
 
 The purpose of this editor is create a header file or edit an existing one.
 The labeled text fields is where the information is entered. The fields are
 self explanatory except for the following:
 
 Land           The  1 to 3  letter country  code should be  entered not the
                full   country  name,   ie;  'D'   should  be   entered  for
                Deutschland.
 
 Telefon        '/' Sould  be entered as the separator between area code and
                telephone number, ie; '06181/259599'.
 
 Telefax        See 'Telefon' above.
 
 Pseudo         Check to  see that you desired Pseudo does not conflict with
                one  already being used.  See the latest  issue of 'Computer
                Flohmarkt'. Also you may need to complete a Pseudoantrag.
 
 AdressNr       You will  receive an address number when your biete or suche
                software list is published. Until then leave this blank.
 
 Zeichensatz    You may not change this field.
 
 Zeitschrift    'CF'   means   'Computer   Flohmarkt'.   'PCH'   means   'PC
                Heimwerker'. This  program was  written to  accommodate 'CF'
                contributors.  If you change this  field, you must also save
                your file under 'PCH.TXT'. See the latest issue of 'Computer
                Flohmarkt' for details.
 Be sure to  press the 'Enter' key after changing a field to ensure that the
 new  info is  accepted. Fill  out the  header information  as completely as
 possible. Without this information your ad may not be published.
 
 The 'Save' button saves the header and takes you back to the 'user window'.
 
 'Cancel'  takes  you back  to the  'user  window'without saving  the header
 information.
 
@ENDNODE

@NODE 0.2.4.2. "text editor"
 
 This is where ads, infos, etc. are entered. The name of the current user is
 displayed  in the  window  title bar.  On th  left side  of the  window are
 buttons.  On the right  is a large  list gadget with  scroll bars along the
 right  and bottom edges. This  is where the text  is entered. On the bottom
 edge  of the window is  a white rectangle. This  is where you end variables
 for  the current are displayed.  By pressing the mouse  button you will see
 the 'delete a file' item under the 'files' menu.
 
 The  'Load', 'Save', and 'Save  As' buttons are used  to load and save text
 files.
 
 NOTE:  Before a  text file  can be  saved, a  rubrik and  at least  one end
 variable must be selected.
 
 Use meaningful  names when saving files. An ad offering a harddisk for sale
 might  be saved under the name 'hdisk_for_sale'.  All files that will later
 be  sent  to  'CF' must  be  written  to  the 'CF'  directory  in  the user
 directory. This is where AmiCFA looks for text files.
 
 Example: AmiCFA  is located on volume 'Work:'. A text file has been written
 for  a user named  'Bob'. This  file should be  saved with the  path name -
 'Work:AmiCFA/Bob/CF/hdisk_for_sale'.
 
 NOTE:  If you  do not change  the path in  the file  requester, AmiCFA will
 always save the files in the correct directory.
 
 The 'Rubrik' button takes you to the 'rubrik selector'. The text field just
 below this button will display the current rubrik number. If you know which
 rubrik number  to use (such as an answer  to a question), you may also type
 it  directly into  this field. The  rubrik number  will also  appear on the
 first line in the text area. Do not change this! Also, do not enter text on
 the  same line with the  rubrik number. The actual  ad text should begin on
 the second line in the text entry window. If you enter text before choosing
 a rubrik,  the text will be automatically moved  to the second line to make
 room for the rubrik number.
 
 The  'Absatz' button allows you  to mark the beginning  of a new paragraph.
 This is not needed in an ad of normal length. However long-winded users may
 find  this handy when typing lengthy infos,  answers or questions. Like the
 rubrik number,  the absatz keyword should be on  a line with no other text.
 Additional text should start on the next line.
 
 The  'ProgEin/Aus' buttons allow you  to mark the start  and end of program
 code listings.
 
 The  'EndVars'  button  takes  you to  the  'end  variables  selector'. End
 variables  determine what information  is printed after  the ad text (name,
 telephone number, etc.).
 
 'Return' takes you back to the 'user window'.
 
 The  menu item 'Delete  a file'  allows you to  delete an old  or no longer
 needed file from disk.
 
 The text  area is where the currently loaded text is displayed and changed.
 A simple  form of word-wrapping is performed. This word-wrapping limits the
 length  of a normal line  to 55 characters and  a program listing (when the
 'ProgEin'  is active) to 40  characters. The word-wrap  is only active when
 the cursor is at the end of the last line of text. Text will not be wrapped
 when typing in the middle of the text.
 
 NOTE:  The  editors of  the 'Computer  Flohmarkt'  will reformat  your text
 before  publishing  it, anyway.  The  word-wrap is  only  to keep  the text
 visible while being edited.
 
 To  enter text  in the text  area, anywhere inside  it with  the mouse. You
 should  then  see a  cursor. Anything  you  type is  always entered  at the
 current  cursor position. The '#'  symbol should not be  used in your text.
 '#' marks the beginning of keywords, ie; #ABSATZ or #RUBRIK.
 
 Several functions are available to make text editing easier:
 
 function                           key press
 --------                           ---------
 Move to start of text              left amiga - home (7 on the number pad)
 Move to end of text                left amiga - end  (1 on the number pad)
 Move cursor                        arrow keys
 delete character left              backspace key
 delete character under cursor      "Del" key
 
 mark start of block                double-click left mouse button
 (end of block is always the current cursor position)
 
 cut                                right amiga - x
 (deletes  from start of block to current  cursor position and places a copy
 in the paste buffer)
 
 copy                               right amiga - c
 (places a copy of the marked block in the paste buffer)
 
 paste                              right amiga - v
 (inserts the contents of the paste buffer at the current cursor position)
 
 NOTE: cut,  copy, and paste are line-based functions. Only entire lines are
 affected.
 
@ENDNODE

@NODE 0.2.4.3. "rubrik selector"
 
 The  'rubrik selector' makes  it easy to  find the right  rubrik number for
 your  ad. The top  of this window is  filled with a  list gadget. Here, the
 main  rubrik topic  are  shown. The  list may  be scrolled  up and  down by
 dragging  the scroll bar on the  right side of the  list. By clicking on an
 item in  the list, you cause the valid  rubrik numbers for this topic to be
 displayed in  the list and the topic will  be shown in the upper text field
 below the list.
 
 An entry in the list might look like this:
 
 1740 Kontakte/Erfahrungsaustausch FRAGE ANTWORT INFO
 
 To select a rubrik click on the line. If the words FRAGE ANTWORT INFO BIETE
 or  SUCHE appear at  the end of  the line, you  must click on  one of these
 words.
 
 To 'back up'  to the main topic list, click on the small button next to the
 field displaying the current main topic.
 
 Click on the 'return' button when finished.
 
@ENDNODE

@NODE 0.2.4.4. "end variable selector"
 
 At the  bottom of each ad certain information  is to be displayed such as a
 name  and  telephone  number,  or  a  mailing  address.  The  'end variable
 selector'  where  you determine  what information  will  be printed  at the
 bottom of the ad currently being edited.
 The buttons  above the white field each represent a valid variable from the
 header.
 
 The white field shows the selected variables.
 
 The  'Start Again' button  clears all variables.  The 'Return' button takes
 you back to the 'text editor'.
 
 When a button has been clicked, the variable appears in the white field and
 the button can not be selected again.
 
 Selecting 'Anschrift' is the same as selecting 'Vorname', 'Name', 'Straße',
 'Land',  'Plz',  and  'Ort'.  Selecting  any  of  these  alone  causes  the
 'Anschrift' variable to be disabled. If you make a mistake, click on 'Start
 Again'.
 
 'Vermerk' can only be selected immediately after 'Telefon'.
 
 NOTE: At least  one variable must be selected to allow you to return to the
 'text editor'
 
@ENDNODE

@NODE 0.2.4.5. "database editor"
 
 This is where biete and suche software lists are created. The user and mode
 (biete or  suche) are displayed in the window title bar. Also in the window
 title bar is info about the current list  in the form of 'Item X of Y'. 'X'
 is the item  number being displayed and 'Y' is the total number of items in
 the  list. To complete a software  entry you must fill  in each of the text
 fields. The  only field in which an entry  is not required is the 'vermerk'
 field.
 
 Those fields with a small button to right must contain one of several valid
 entries. If you click on one of these buttons, all of the valid entries for
 that field will be displayed in the list gadget in the lower left corner of
 the  window. By clicking  on an entry  in the list  gadget, the valid value
 will automatically be entered in the field. The list gadget may be scrolled
 up and down by dragging the scroll bar running along its right side.
 
 After filling in  all the text fields, you must check to see that the radio
 buttons reflect the correct information, ie; gebraucht or neu, etc.
 
 To  add an entry to the  list click on 'add entry',  to delete one click on
 'delete entry'.
 
 Click  on the 'prev' button  to view the previous  entry and 'next' to view
 the next entry.
 
 To save your  changed data, click on 'save' and then 'return' to got to the
 'user window'.
 
 NOTE:  To  completely delete  the database  file  from disk,  click 'delete
 entry' until the window title bar shows 'Item 1 of 1' and the current entry
 is  blank. Then click on 'return'. After  a warning, the database file will
 be deleted from disk. It is a good idea to always delete an empty database.
 
@ENDNODE

